{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Unsupported `cook` actions silently clear the deferred solvency check","locations":["cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:456","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:488","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:527","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:538"],"claim":"`cook()` defers the post-action solvency check by setting `status.needsSolvencyCheck = true` after `ACTION_BORROW` and `ACTION_REMOVE_COLLATERAL`, but any unhandled action falls through to the base `_additionalCookAction()` implementation, which is an empty no-op returning a zero-initialized `CookStatus`. That overwrites the pending status and clears `needsSolvencyCheck`, so the final `require(_isSolvent(...))` is skipped entirely. The declared-but-unhandled `ACTION_ACCRUE` (`8`) is one such built-in bypass.","impact":"An attacker can borrow MIM or remove collateral through `cook()` without remaining solvent. This enables undercollateralized or fully uncollateralized debt up to the market's borrow caps and available MIM liquidity, creating immediate bad debt and potentially draining the pool.","paths":["Call `cook([ACTION_BORROW, ACTION_ACCRUE], ...)` so `_borrow()` transfers out MIM, then the unhandled second action resets `status` and the transaction exits without the final solvency check.","Call `cook([ACTION_REMOVE_COLLATERAL, <any unsupported action>], ...)` to withdraw collateral and then erase the pending solvency check before the loop finishes."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"A zero oracle rate is treated as valid, making dust-collateralized debt appear solvent and unliquidatable","locations":["cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:158","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:201","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:226","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:578"],"claim":"The contract accepts and stores an `exchangeRate` of zero, both during initialization and during normal oracle refreshes. `_isSolvent()` multiplies debt by `_exchangeRate`, so when the cached rate is zero the debt side of the solvency inequality becomes zero; any borrower with `borrowPart > 0` and at least 1 collateral share therefore passes solvency. `liquidate()` uses the same predicate, so those accounts are also skipped as supposedly solvent.","impact":"If the oracle ever reports `(true, 0)` or the cache is otherwise set to zero, an attacker can post dust collateral, borrow most or all available MIM, and remove nearly all collateral while keeping a single share behind. The resulting position remains marked solvent and cannot be liquidated, leaving the market with bad debt and drained liquidity.","paths":["A zero-valued oracle response is cached through `updateExchangeRate()` or seeded at deployment.","The attacker adds minimal collateral, borrows available MIM, removes collateral down to 1 share, and `liquidate()` keeps reverting with all targets considered solvent under the zero rate."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"`init()` ignores the oracle success flag and can seed a poisoned cached price at deployment","locations":["cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:148","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:158","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:160","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:233"],"claim":"During clone initialization, `init()` stores the raw `rate` from `oracle.get(oracleData)` without checking the returned `success` boolean. A failing oracle response such as `(false, 0)` therefore seeds `exchangeRate` with an invalid value at deployment. Because later failed refreshes preserve the cached value, the market can stay poisoned until someone obtains a successful oracle update.","impact":"A newly deployed market can come online already carrying a broken cached price. If the failed initialization response sets `exchangeRate` to zero or another unrealistic value, the market can be immediately mispriced and, in the zero-rate case, drainable before any successful refresh repairs the cache.","paths":["Deploy a new clone while the oracle returns `(false, 0)` during `init()`.","Before any successful `updateExchangeRate()` occurs, use the poisoned cached rate to borrow against negligible collateral or otherwise exploit the mispricing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Borrowing, collateral withdrawals, and liquidation decisions continue against stale prices when oracle updates fail","locations":["cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:218","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:226","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:233","cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:539"],"claim":"`updateExchangeRate()` does not halt risk-sensitive actions when `oracle.get()` fails; it simply returns the previously cached `exchangeRate`. The `solvent` modifier used by `borrow()` and `removeCollateral()`, as well as the deferred check at the end of `cook()`, all accept that stale rate instead of requiring a fresh oracle result. `liquidate()` also uses the same stale cached rate after a failed update.","impact":"During an oracle outage, positions continue to be judged against an outdated price. After a sharp market move, borrowers can over-borrow or withdraw too much collateral at a stale favorable valuation, while liquidations may lag the true market state and allow bad debt to accumulate.","paths":["Collateral price moves materially off-chain, but `oracle.get()` begins failing.","A borrower calls `borrow()`, `removeCollateral()`, or `cook()` and passes solvency checks using the old cached price instead of the current one.","Liquidators are forced to evaluate positions using the same stale rate, so underwater accounts may remain effectively unliquidatable until oracle updates recover."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Public clone initialization is first-come-first-served if deployment is ever non-atomic","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"This depends on an out-of-scope, non-atomic clone deployment flow that is not shown in the in-scope cod